Load data from Kaggle:¶

Step 1: Download API Credentials¶

To download data from Kaggle, you need to authenticate with the Kaggle services. For this purpose, you need an API token. This token can be easily generated from the profile section of your Kaggle account. If you dont have an account yet, create one. Else, navigate to your Kaggle profile and then

download API credentials Click the Account tab and then scroll down to the API section (Screenshot from Kaggle profile)

A file named “kaggle.json” will be download which contains the username and the API key.

This is a one-time step and you don’t need to generate the credentials every time you download the dataset.

Step 2: Setup the Colab Notebook¶

On a Google Colab notebook, connect to the cloud instance (basically start the notebook interface). Then, upload the “kaggle.json” file that you just downloaded from Kaggle.

Now you are all set to run the commands need to load the dataset. Follow along with these commands:

Note: Here we will run all the Linux and installation commands starting with “!”. As Colab instances are Linux-based, you can run all the Linux commands in the code cells. run the code bellow:

About the dataset¶

It is created by Dr.Kristen Gorman and the Palmer Station, Antarctica LTER. This dataset is essentially composed of two datasets, each containing the data of 344 penguins.

In this dataset, there are 3 different species of penguins coming from 3 islands in the Palmer Archipelago. These three classes are Adelie, Chinstrap, and Gentoo.

Also, these datasets contain culmen dimensions for each species. The culmen is the upper ridge of a bird’s bill. we will use features based on penguins’ culmen measurement. You can learn more about the penguins’ culmen with the illustration below:

In the simplified penguin’s data, culmen length and depth are renamed as variables culmen_length_mm and culmen_depth_mm.

Task 2:¶

Remove NAs

Use label encoder to encode categorical values

Create an X dataframe containing the features and a y vector with only the'species' column.

Split the data into train and test with 10% for the test

In [8]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

data.dropna(inplace=True)

species_le = LabelEncoder()
data['species'] = species_le.fit_transform(data['species'])
island_le = LabelEncoder()
data['island'] = island_le.fit_transform(data['island'])
sex_le = LabelEncoder()
data['sex'] = sex_le.fit_transform(data['sex'])

X = data.iloc[:, 1:]
y = data.iloc[:, 0]

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.1, random_state=11)

column_names = X.columns

Task 3:¶

Create a simple decision tree using sklearn.tree.DecisionTreeClassifier.

Choose the criteria, max depth, and min samples split parameters as you see fit.

For each parameter try 2 different values - total of 8 models

Train your model on the train set.

In [9]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier

criterion = ["gini", "entropy"]
max_depth = [2, 6]
min_samples_split = [10, 30]
trees = {}

for item1 in criterion:
  for item2 in max_depth:
    for item3 in min_samples_split:
      model = DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion=item1, max_depth=item2, min_samples_split=item3)
      model.fit(X_train, y_train)
      trees[(item1, item2, item3)] = model

Task 4:¶

Select the best model by testing on the test set, caculate accuracy and print it with 3 digits after the floating point

Plot the selected model using sklearn.tree.plot_tree

Does your model overfit? what can you do to fix it? (in your answer refer to criterion, max_depth, min_samples_split)

In [11]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from sklearn.tree import plot_tree

accuracies = {}
for tree in trees.keys():
  preds = trees[tree].predict(X_test)
  accuracies[tree] = accuracy_score(y_test, preds)


accuracies = sorted(accuracies.items(), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
selected_model = trees[accuracies[0][0]]
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(13, 13))
plot_tree(selected_model, ax=ax, fontsize=10, feature_names=column_names)
plt.show()

# to check for overfitting we should calculate train accuray 
preds = selected_model.predict(X_train)
print('train accuracy is: ', accuracy_score(y_train, preds))
print('test accuracy is: ', accuracies[0][1])

train accuracy is:  0.9866666666666667
test accuracy is:  0.9705882352941176

The model does not overfit . if it was - we could reduce the max depth or increase the min split size.
